      "title": "Defining the Intangible Product",
      "content": "An intangible product is, by definition, something you cannot physically touch, hold, or store in a warehouse. Its value lies not in its physical form but in the experience, right, or benefit it provides. A concert ticket is a perfect illustration of this concept. The physical paper or digital QR code is merely the proof of purchase; the product itself is the 'right to participate' in a live event. This distinction is critical. When you sell a physical product, you are transferring ownership of an object. When you sell a ticket, you are granting access and creating an expectation of an experience. The value is entirely experiential and psychological. This means the sales process must focus on the anticipated emotion, the networking potential, or the knowledge gain, rather than the features of a tangible item. The product is the promise of a future event, a promise that must be managed with care."
